<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ871117-0031 </DOCNO><HL> Imperial Corp. UnitStarts Notes Offering</HL><DD> 11/17/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><IN> ICABOND MARKET NEWS (BON) </IN><DATELINE> SAN DIEGO  </DATELINE><TEXT>   Imperial Corp. of America said its thrift unit, Imperial Savings Association, began a public offering of $500 million of collateralized medium-term notes, with maturities ranging from nine months to 15 years.    The notes will be secured in part by high-yielding corporate debt, or &quot;junk&quot; bonds. Imperial said it expects the notes to be rated triple-A by both Moody's Investors Service Inc. and Standard andamp; Poor's Corp. Interest is payable semiannually. The notes are being offered on a continuous basis by an underwriting group led by Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.    Imperial said it will use proceeds for lending and other general corporate purposes. As previously reported, Imperial Savings in September sold $100 million of 9.375% collateralized notes secured by junk bonds. </TEXT></DOC>